[{"id":32277,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>9</mn><mn>16</mn></mfrac><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>16</mn><mn>9</mn></mfrac><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>3</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>4</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>For H-atom,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi></msub><mo>&#8733;</mo><mfrac><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">z</mi></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msup><mn>3</mn><mn>2</mn></msup><msup><mn>4</mn><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>9</mn><mn>16</mn></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>16</mn><mn>9</mn></mfrac><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (26 Jun Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":32253,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>The orbitals oriented along axis have electron density along the axis.</p><p>Orientation of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi></math>&nbsp;orbitals are as follows:<br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/36a75086-896f-434c-b25c-7e8a479d80a8-9894610.png\" style=\"width: 400px; height: 365px;\" /></p><p>Orientation of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">z</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></msub><mo>&#38;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mrow><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>-</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">y</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></msub><mo>:</mo></math><br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/22360c99-cb7b-4c4b-8c22-9072de9ec01e-9894610_2.png\" style=\"width: 500px; height: 310px;\" />,&nbsp;<br /><br />Thus,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi></msub><mo>,</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">y</mi></msub><mo>,</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">z</mi></msub><mo>,</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">z</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></msub><mo>&#38;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mrow><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>-</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">y</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></msub></math> are axial orbitals.</p><p>The orbitals&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mi>xy</mi></msub><mo>,</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mi>yz</mi></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>and</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mi>xz</mi></msub></math>&nbsp;are oriented between the axis.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (25 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":32302,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#8467;</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></math></p><p>Hence, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#8467;</mi></math> value must be <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo></math></p><p>Now, number of radial nodes&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#8467;</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (17 Mar Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":32222,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["Statement-I is true but Statement-II is false","Both Statement-I and Statement-II are true.","Both Statement-I and Statement-II are false","Statement-I is false but Statement-II is true"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Degenerate orbitals are the orbitals of the same subshell having equal energies. When the electrons of the orbitals are not influenced by any external factors like an electric field or magnetic field, they have same energies.</p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">For a single electron species like hydrogen atom, the energy depends upon the principal quantum number <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>'</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>'</mo></math> only. Hence, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mn>3</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi><mo> </mo><mi>and</mi><mo> </mo><mn>3</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi></math> oribitals have same energy. So, statement II is false.</p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Statement I is correct definition of degenerate orbitals.</p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Hence, the answer is option A.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (30 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":32352,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["<math><msqrt><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi></msqrt></math>","<math><msqrt><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&nbsp;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi></msqrt></math>","<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi></math>","<math><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"Given, stream of electron from heated filament was passed between two charge plates at potential difference <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi></math>.<br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>and</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math> are charge and mass of electron, respectively.<br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>Energy</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi></mfrac></math><br /><math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">v</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></math><br /><math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#955;</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">h</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">v</mi></mrow></mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">v</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">h</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#955;</mi></mrow></mfrac></math><br /><math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mrow><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\" separators=\"|\"><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">h</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#955;</mi></mrow></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></math><br /><math><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">h</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#955;</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi></msqrt><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2016 (03 Apr)","image":null},{"id":32362,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["<math> <mrow>  <mn>27.2</mn><mtext>&#x2009;</mtext><mtext>eV</mtext></mrow></math>","<math> <mrow> <mo>−</mo><mn>30.6</mn><mtext> </mtext><mtext>eV</mtext></mrow> </math>","<math> <mrow> <mn>30.6</mn><mtext>&#x2009;</mtext><mtext>eV</mtext></mrow></math>","<math> <mrow>  <mo>&#x2212;</mo><mn>27.2</mn><mtext>&#x2009;</mtext><mtext>eV</mtext></mrow></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"For H&nbsp;atom &amp; H like species<br />The electronic energy in the nth orbit is<br /><br /><math> <mrow> <msub> <mtext>E</mtext> <mtext>n</mtext> </msub> <mo>=</mo> <mo>-</mo> <mtext>13.6</mtext> <mfrac> <mrow> <msup> <mtext>z</mtext> <mn>2</mn> </msup> </mrow> <mrow> <msup> <mtext>n</mtext> <mn>2</mn> </msup> </mrow> </mfrac> <mo>eV</mo> </mrow> </math><br /><br /><math> <mrow> <msub> <mrow> <mfenced close=\")\" open=\"(\" separators=\",\"> <mrow> <msub> <mtext>E</mtext> <mtext>n</mtext> </msub> </mrow> </mfenced> </mrow> <msup> <mtext>Li</mtext> <mrow> <mn>2</mn> <mo>+</mo> </mrow> </msup> </msub> <mo>=</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <mo>-</mo> <mtext>13.6</mtext> <mo>×</mo> <mn>9</mn> </mrow> <mrow> <msup> <mtext>n</mtext> <mn>2</mn> </msup> </mrow> </mfrac> <mo>eV</mo> <mo>=</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <mo>-</mo> <mtext>122.4 eV</mtext> </mrow> <mrow> <msup> <mtext>n</mtext> <mn>2</mn> </msup> </mrow> </mfrac> </mrow> </math><br /><br />If n = 2<br /><br /><math> <mrow> <msub> <mrow> <mfenced close=\")\" open=\"(\" separators=\",\"> <mrow> <msub> <mtext>E</mtext> <mn>2</mn> </msub> </mrow> </mfenced> </mrow> <msup> <mtext>Li</mtext> <mrow> <mn>2</mn> <mo>+</mo> </mrow> </msup> </msub> <mo>=</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <mo>-</mo> <mtext>122.4</mtext> </mrow> <mrow> <msup> <mtext>2</mtext> <mn>2</mn> </msup> </mrow> </mfrac> <mo>=</mo> <mo>-</mo> <mtext>30.6 eV</mtext> </mrow> </math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2014 (09 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":32170,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["$1.4,2.8$","$2.3,4.6$","$1.5,3.0$","$3.1,6.2$"],"answer":1,"solution":"The work functions satisfy $W_A : W_B = 1:2$.<br>Let $W_A = W$ and $W_B = 2W$.<br>Using the photoelectric equation<br>$KE = h\\nu - W$, we have $KE_A = 6 - W$ and $KE_B = 6 - 2W$.<br>Given the kinetic energy ratio $\\frac{KE_A}{KE_B} = 2.642$, we get $\\frac{6-W}{6-2W} = 2.642$.<br>Solving: $6 - W = 2.642(6 - 2W)$ gives $6 - W = 15.852 - 5.284W$<br>So $4.284W = 9.852$ and $W = 2.3$ eV.<br>Thus $W_A = 2.3$ eV and $W_B = 4.6$ eV.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (23 January Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":32357,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["$\\frac{1}{2} \\frac{e^2}{r}$","$-\\frac{e^2}{r}$","$\\frac{m e^2}{r}$","$-\\frac{1}{2} \\frac{e^2}{r}$"],"answer":3,"solution":"Total energy of a revolving electron is the sum of its kinetic and potential energy. Total energy $=$ K.E. $+$ P. E.\n$$\n=\\frac{e^2}{2 r}+\\left(-\\frac{e^2}{r}\\right)=-\\frac{e^2}{2 r}\n$$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2014 (12 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":32160,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["$n = 3, l = 2, m = +2, s = +\\dfrac{1}{2}$","$n = 3, l = 2, m = -2, s = +\\dfrac{1}{2}$","$n = 4, l = 1, m = 0, s = +\\dfrac{1}{2}$","$n = 4, l = 0, m = 0, s = +\\dfrac{1}{2}$"],"answer":3,"solution":"The atomic number of Chromium is $24$.<br><br>According to the Aufbau principle, the order of filling of electrons is $1s, 2s, 2p, 3s, 3p, 4s, 3d$.<br><br>The electronic configuration of the first $18$ electrons is $1s^2 2s^2 2p^6 3s^2 3p^6$.<br><br>The $19^{th}$ electron enters the $4s$ orbital.<br><br>For the $4s$ orbital, the quantum numbers are:<br>Principal quantum number, $n = 4$<br>Azimuthal quantum number, $l = 0$<br>Magnetic quantum number, $m = 0$<br>Spin quantum number, $s = +\\dfrac{1}{2}$ or $-\\dfrac{1}{2}$<br><br>This matches the set given in the fourth option.<br><br>Answer: $n = 4, l = 0, m = 0, s = +\\dfrac{1}{2}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (04 April Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":32262,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["A circular path around the nucleus in which an electron moves is proposed as Bohr&#39;s orbit.","An orbital is the one electron wave function","The existence of Bohr&#39;s orbits is supported by hydrogen spectrum.","Atomic orbital is characterised by the quantum numbers <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi></math>&nbsp;only"],"answer":3,"solution":"<blockquote><p>An electron can move only in those orbits for which its angular momentum is integral multiple of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">h</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#960;</mi></mrow></mfrac></math>. That means angular momentum is quantised. Radiation is emitted or absorbed only when transition of electron takes place from one quantised value of angular momentum to another. Therefore. Maxwell&#39;s electromagnetic theory does not apply here that is why only certain fixed orbits are allowed. Atomic orbital is characterised by <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math>. So, the option D is incorrect.</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (28 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":32159,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["$5:1$","$5:0.81$","$5:1.75$","$5:27$"],"answer":1,"solution":"The wave number $\\bar{\\nu}$ of a spectral line in the hydrogen emission spectrum is given by the Rydberg formula:<br><br>$\\bar{\\nu} = R_H \\left( \\dfrac{1}{n_1^2} - \\dfrac{1}{n_2^2} \\right)$<br><br>For the first line (lowest energy) of the Balmer series, the transition is from $n_2 = 3$ to $n_1 = 2$:<br><br>$\\bar{\\nu}_{Balmer} = R_H \\left( \\dfrac{1}{2^2} - \\dfrac{1}{3^2} \\right) = R_H \\left( \\dfrac{1}{4} - \\dfrac{1}{9} \\right) = \\dfrac{5R_H}{36}$<br><br>For the first line of the Brackett series, the transition is from $n_2 = 5$ to $n_1 = 4$:<br><br>$\\bar{\\nu}_{Brackett} = R_H \\left( \\dfrac{1}{4^2} - \\dfrac{1}{5^2} \\right) = R_H \\left( \\dfrac{1}{16} - \\dfrac{1}{25} \\right) = \\dfrac{9R_H}{400}$<br><br>Taking the ratio of the two wave numbers:<br><br>$\\dfrac{\\bar{\\nu}_{Balmer}}{\\bar{\\nu}_{Brackett}} = \\dfrac{\\dfrac{5R_H}{36}}{\\dfrac{9R_H}{400}} = \\dfrac{5}{36} \\times \\dfrac{400}{9} = \\dfrac{500}{81}$<br><br>To express this ratio in the form $5 : x$, we divide the numerator and the denominator by $100$:<br><br>$\\dfrac{500}{81} = \\dfrac{5}{0.81}$<br><br>The ratio is $5 : 0.81$.<br><br>Answer: $5:0.81$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (04 April Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":32263,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></mfenced><mo>&#62;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mfenced><mo>&#62;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mfenced><mo>&#62;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mfenced></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mfenced><mo>&#62;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></mfenced><mo>&#62;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mfenced><mo>&#62;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mfenced></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mfenced><mo>&#62;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mfenced><mo>&#62;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></mfenced><mo>&#62;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mfenced></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mfenced><mo>&#62;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mfenced><mo>&#62;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></mfenced><mo>&#62;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mfenced></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>(A) <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>+</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn></math><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mn>3</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></math></p><p>(B)&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>+</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn></math><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mn>4</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></math></p><p>(C) <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>+</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn></math><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mn>3</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi></math></p><p>(D)&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>+</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn></math><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mn>3</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi></math></p><p>Higher the&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>+</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi></math> value, higher the energy of the orbital and if two orbitals have same <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>+</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi></math>&nbsp;value, then the orbital with higher <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi></math> value has higher&nbsp;energy.</p><p>Thus:&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>.</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (27 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":32193,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["(A) and (C) only","(B) and (D) only","(C) and (D) only","(A) and (B) only"],"answer":2,"solution":"For single electron species energy only depends on ' n ' (principal quantum number)\n\nSo energy of $2 \\mathrm{~s}=2 \\mathrm{p}$\nand energy of $3 \\mathrm{~d} < 4 \\mathrm{~s}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (28 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":32365,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["$6.626 \\times 10^{-34} \\mathrm{~m}$","$6.626 \\times 10^{-38} \\mathrm{~m}$","$6.626 \\times 10^{-31} \\mathrm{~m}$","$6.626 \\times 10^{-30} \\mathrm{~m}$"],"answer":1,"solution":"$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n& \\text { } \\lambda=\\frac{h}{m v} \\\\\n& h=6.6 \\times 10^{-34} \\mathrm{~J}-\\mathrm{s} \\\\\n& m=1000 \\mathrm{~kg} \\\\\n& v=36 \\mathrm{~km} / \\mathrm{hr}=\\frac{36 \\times 10^3}{60 \\times 60} \\mathrm{~m} / \\mathrm{sec}=10 \\mathrm{~m} / \\mathrm{sec} \\\\\n& \\therefore \\quad \\lambda=\\frac{6.6 \\times 10^{-34}}{10^3 \\times 10}=6.6 \\times 10^{-38} \\mathrm{~m} \\\\\n&\n\\end{aligned}\n$$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (23 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":32372,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["$4 \\pi a_0$","$8 \\pi a_0$","$6 \\pi a_0$","$2 \\pi a_0$"],"answer":2,"solution":"$r_n=a_0 n^2$\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n& r=a_0 \\times(3)^2=9 a_0 \\\\\n& m v r=\\frac{n h}{2 \\pi} \\\\\n& m v=\\frac{n h}{2 \\pi \\mathrm{r}}=\\frac{3 h}{2 \\pi \\times 9 a_0}=\\frac{h}{6 \\pi a_0} \\\\\n& \\lambda=\\frac{h}{m v}=\\frac{h}{h} \\times 6 \\pi a_0=6 \\pi a_0\n\\end{aligned}\n$$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2012 (12 May Online)","image":null},{"id":32219,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mfrac><mrow></mrow><mrow></mrow></mfrac></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>The set of numbers used to describe the position and energy of the electron in an atom are called quantum numbers. There are four quantum numbers, namely, principal, azimuthal, magnetic and spin quantum numbers.</p><p>Electronic configuration of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi></math> is:</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mo>=</mo><mo> </mo><mi>Atomic</mi><mo> </mo><mi>number</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>19</mn><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mn>1</mn><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mn>2</mn><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mn>2</mn><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi><mn>6</mn></msup><mn>3</mn><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mn>3</mn><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi><mn>6</mn></msup><mn>4</mn><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mn>1</mn></msup></math></p><p>The outermost electron is in <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><msup><mi>s</mi><mn>1</mn></msup></math></p><p>∴ <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math></p><p>Hence, the answer is option B.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (31 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":32226,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>[</mo><mi>Xe</mi><mo>]</mo><mo> </mo><mn>4</mn><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi><mn>4</mn></msup><mo> </mo><mn>6</mn><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>[</mo><mi>Xe</mi><mo>]</mo><mo> </mo><mn>5</mn><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi><mn>4</mn></msup><mn>7</mn><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>[</mo><mi>Xe</mi><mo>]</mo><mo> </mo><mn>4</mn><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi><mn>6</mn></msup><mo> </mo><mn>6</mn><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>[</mo><mi>Xe</mi><mo>]</mo><mo> </mo><mn>4</mn><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi><mn>1</mn></msup><mn>5</mn><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mn>1</mn></msup><mn>6</mn><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>The atomic number of neodymium is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>60</mn></math>.</p><p>Therefore, the electronic configuration of neodymium (Nd) can be determined by distributing its electrons according to the Aufbau principle, Pauli exclusion principle, and Hund's rule.</p><p>Electronic configuration of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Nd</mi><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi><mo> </mo><mo>=</mo><mo> </mo><mn>60</mn><mo>)</mo></math> is;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>[</mo><mi>Xe</mi><mo>]</mo><mo> </mo><mn>4</mn><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi><mn>4</mn></msup><mn>6</mn><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math></p><p>as the last electron of Neodymium enters the f subshell. so it is called a f-block element.</p><p>Hence option A is the answer.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (27 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":32290,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["All of the <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#945;</mi></math>-particles pass through the gold foil without decrease in speed.","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#945;</mi></math>-particles are deflected over a wide range of angles.","All <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#945;</mi></math>-particles get bounced back by <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>180</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math>.","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#945;</mi></math>-particles pass through the gold foil deflected by small angles and with reduced speed."],"answer":3,"solution":"According to Thomson&#39;s plum pudding model, protons are diffused in a positively charged cloud (charge is not centred) and the negatively charged particles are embedded in&nbsp;it. So, the&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#945;</mi></math>- particles would deviate by small angles and due to repulsion from protons, their speed would decrease.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (27 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":32189,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["3.87 and 4.90 B.M.","4.90 and 5.92 B.M.","4.90 and 4.90 B.M.","5.92 and 4.90 B.M."],"answer":3,"solution":"$\\begin{aligned}\n& \\mathrm{K}_3\\left[\\mathrm{Fe}(\\mathrm{OH})_6\\right] \\\\\n& \\mathrm{Fe}^{3+} \\Rightarrow 3 \\mathrm{~d}^5 \\\\\n& \\mathrm{Fe}^{3+} \\text { with } \\mathrm{OH}^{-}(\\mathrm{WFL}) \\\\\n& =\\mathrm{t}_{29}{ }^3 \\mathrm{e}_{\\mathrm{g}}{ }^2\n\\end{aligned}$\n\nNumber of unpaired electron ( $n$ ) $=5$\n$\\mu$ spin only $=5.92 \\mathrm{BM}$\n$\\begin{aligned}\n& \\mathrm{K}_4\\left[\\mathrm{Fe}(\\mathrm{OH})_6\\right] \\\\\n& \\mathrm{Fe}^{2+} \\Rightarrow \\mathrm{OH}^{-} \\mathrm{(WFL)} \\\\\n& \\mathrm{Fe}^{2+} \\Rightarrow 3 \\mathrm{~d}^6=\\mathrm{t}_{2 \\mathrm{~g}}^4 \\mathrm{e}_{\\mathrm{g}}^2 \\\\\n& \\mathrm{n}=4\n\\end{aligned}$\n$\\mu_{\\text {spin only }}=4.90 \\mathrm{BM}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (29 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":32191,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["Statement I is incorrect but Statement II is correct","Statement I is correct but Statement II is incorrect","Both Statement I and Statement II are incorrect","Both Statement I and Statement II are correct"],"answer":3,"solution":"$\\mathrm{r} \\propto \\mathrm{q}^{-}$(for isoelectronic species)\n$\\propto \\frac{1}{q^{+}}$\n$\\therefore$ Statement I is correct\nMagnitude of electron gain enthalpy\n$\\mathrm{Cl}>\\mathrm{F}>\\mathrm{Br}>\\mathrm{I}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (29 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":32310,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#955;</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">h</mi><msqrt><mn>2</mn><mi>mqV</mi></msqrt></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><msub><mi>&#955;</mi><mi>Li</mi></msub><msub><mi>&#955;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi></msub><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi></mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi></mrow><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mi>Li</mi></msub><mfenced><mrow><mn>3</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi></mrow></mfenced><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi></mfenced></mrow></mfrac></msqrt><mo>&#160;&#160;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mi>Li</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi></msub></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><msub><mi>&#955;</mi><mi>Li</mi></msub><msub><mi>&#955;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mn>8</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></mfrac></msqrt><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>5</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (24 Feb Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":32380,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["$1.52 \\times 10^{-4} \\mathrm{~m}$","$5.10 \\times 10^{-3} \\mathrm{~m}$","$1.92 \\times 10^{-3} \\mathrm{~m}$","$3.84 \\times 10^{-3} \\mathrm{~m}$"],"answer":2,"solution":"$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n& \\Delta \\mathrm{x} . \\mathrm{m} \\Delta \\mathrm{v}=\\frac{\\mathrm{h}}{4 \\pi} \\\\\n& \\Delta \\mathrm{x}=\\frac{\\mathrm{h}}{4 \\pi \\mathrm{m} \\Delta \\mathrm{v}} \\\\\n& \\Delta \\mathrm{v}=600 \\times \\frac{0.005}{100}=0.03 \\\\\n& \\Rightarrow \\Delta \\mathrm{x}=\\frac{6.625 \\times 10^{-34}}{4 \\times 3.14 \\times 9.1 \\times 10^{-31} \\times 0.03}=1.92 \\times 10^{-3} \\mathrm{~m}\n\\end{aligned}\n$$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2009","image":null},{"id":32275,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#916;V</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>26</mn></mrow></msup><msup><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>ms</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#916;x</mi><mo>=</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>7</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8757;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>&#916;p</mi><mo>&#183;</mo><mi>&#916;x</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">h</mi><mrow><mn>4</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#960;</mi></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8756;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>m&#916;V</mi><mo>.</mo><mi>&#916;x</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">h</mi><mrow><mn>4</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#960;</mi></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>26</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>7</mn></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>626</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>34</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#960;</mi></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>626</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>9</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#960;</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>02198</mn><mi>kg</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>21</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>98</mn><mi>gm</mi></math></p><p>nearest integer&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>22</mn></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (27 Jun Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":32231,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"The orbital angular momentum<br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">=</mi><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">h</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#960;</mi></mrow></mfrac><msqrt><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced></msqrt></math><br /><br />For <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></math>-electron, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math>.<br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8756;</mo></math>&nbsp;The orbital angular momentum<br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">h</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mtext>&#960;</mtext></mrow></mfrac><msqrt><mn>0</mn><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced></msqrt></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>0&#160;</mn><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mi>zero</mi></mfenced></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (13 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":32296,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>[</mo><mi>Kr</mi><mo>]</mo><mn>3</mn><msup><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi></mrow><mn>10</mn></msup><mn>4</mn><msup><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></mrow><mn>2</mn></msup><mn>4</mn><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>[</mo><mi>Ar</mi><mo>]</mo><mn>3</mn><msup><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi></mrow><mn>10</mn></msup><mn>4</mn><msup><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></mrow><mn>2</mn></msup><mn>4</mn><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>[</mo><mi>Xe</mi><mo>]</mo><mn>5</mn><msup><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi></mrow><mn>10</mn></msup><mn>6</mn><msup><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></mrow><mn>2</mn></msup><mn>6</mn><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>[</mo><mi>Kr</mi><mo>]</mo><mn>4</mn><msup><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi></mrow><mn>10</mn></msup><mn>5</mn><msup><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></mrow><mn>2</mn></msup><mn>5</mn><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"The element <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi></math> is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Ga</mi></math> and the diagonal element of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mn>5</mn><mtext>th&#160;</mtext></msup></math> period is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mmultiscripts><mi>Sn</mi><mprescripts/><mn>50</mn><none/></mmultiscripts></math> having outer electronic configuration will be <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>[</mo><mi>Kr</mi><mo>]</mo><mn>5</mn><msup><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></mrow><mn>2</mn></msup><mn>4</mn><msup><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi></mrow><mn>10</mn></msup><mn>5</mn><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>.</mo></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (20 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":32388,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{K}^{+}, \\mathrm{Cl}^{-}, \\mathrm{Ca}^{2+}, \\mathrm{Sc}^{3+}$","$\\mathrm{Ba}^{2+}, \\mathrm{Sr}^{2+}, \\mathrm{K}^{+}, \\mathrm{S}^{2-}$","$\\mathrm{N}^{3-}, \\mathrm{O}^{2-}, \\mathrm{F}^{-}, \\mathrm{S}^{2-}$","$\\mathrm{Li}^{+}, \\mathrm{Na}^{+}, \\mathrm{Mg}^{2+}, \\mathrm{Ca}^{2+}$"],"answer":0,"solution":"No Solution Available","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2006","image":null},{"id":32176,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{D}<\\mathrm{C}<\\mathrm{A}<\\mathrm{B}$","$\\mathrm{D}<\\mathrm{A}<\\mathrm{C}<\\mathrm{B}$","$\\mathrm{C}<\\mathrm{D}<\\mathrm{B}<\\mathrm{A}$","$\\mathrm{A}<\\mathrm{B}<\\mathrm{C}<\\mathrm{D}$"],"answer":1,"solution":"The energy of a spectral line in the hydrogen atom is given by $E = 13.6 \\left( \\frac{1}{n_1^2} - \\frac{1}{n_2^2} \\right)$ eV.<br>A. First line of Paschen series: $n_1 = 3, n_2 = 4$.<br>$E_A = 13.6 \\left( \\frac{1}{3^2} - \\frac{1}{4^2} \\right) = 13.6 \\left( \\frac{1}{9} - \\frac{1}{16} \\right) = 13.6 \\times \\frac{7}{144} \\approx 0.66$ eV.<br><br>B. Second line of Balmer series: $n_1 = 2, n_2 = 4$.<br>$E_B = 13.6 \\left( \\frac{1}{2^2} - \\frac{1}{4^2} \\right) = 13.6 \\left( \\frac{1}{4} - \\frac{1}{16} \\right) = 13.6 \\times \\frac{3}{16} = 2.55$ eV.<br><br>C. Third line of Paschen series: $n_1 = 3, n_2 = 6$.<br>$E_C = 13.6 \\left( \\frac{1}{3^2} - \\frac{1}{6^2} \\right) = 13.6 \\left( \\frac{1}{9} - \\frac{1}{36} \\right) = 13.6 \\times \\frac{3}{36} = 13.6 \\times \\frac{1}{12} \\approx 1.13$ eV.<br><br>D. Fourth line of Brackett series: $n_1 = 4, n_2 = 8$.<br>$E_D = 13.6 \\left( \\frac{1}{4^2} - \\frac{1}{8^2} \\right) = 13.6 \\left( \\frac{1}{16} - \\frac{1}{64} \\right) = 13.6 \\times \\frac{3}{64} \\approx 0.6375$ eV.<br><br>Comparing the values: $E_D (0.6375) < E_A (0.66) < E_C (1.13) < E_B (2.55)$.<br>The ascending order of energy is $D < A < C < B$.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (21 January Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":32256,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["1","2","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math>","3"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>The statement of moseley&#39;s law is: &ldquo;The square root of the frequency of the x-ray emitted by an atom is proportional to its atomic number&rdquo;.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msqrt><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">v</mi></msqrt><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#8733;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi></math>&nbsp;So <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math></p><p>Moseley is the scientist most directly responsible for realizing that the structure of the atom is key to understanding the elements themselves.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (24 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":32396,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{K}^{+}, \\mathrm{Ca}^{2+}, \\mathrm{Sc}^{3+}, \\mathrm{Cl}^{-}$","$\\mathrm{Na}^{+}, \\mathrm{Mg}^{2+}, \\mathrm{Al}^{3+}, \\mathrm{Cl}^{-}$","$\\mathrm{K}^{+}, \\mathrm{Cl}^{-}, \\mathrm{Mg}^{2+}, \\mathrm{Sc}^{3+}$","$\\mathrm{Na}^{+}, \\mathrm{Ca}^{2+}, \\mathrm{Sc}^{3+}, \\mathrm{F}^{-}$"],"answer":0,"solution":"No Solution Available","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2004","image":null},{"id":32282,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["Only&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mfenced></math>","Only&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mfenced></math>","Only&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mfenced></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mfenced></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mfenced></math>&nbsp;both"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>The orbitals which have same energy are called&nbsp;degenerate orbitals. Energy or an orbital depends on two quantum numbers, principle quantum number (n) and azimuthal quantum number (l).</p><p>The orbitals with similar values of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#38;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi></math> but with different value of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math>&nbsp;will be degenerate orbitals.</p><p>Among the given set or orbital only option (B)&nbsp;fulfil this condition.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (24 Jun Shift 1)","image":null}]